Headlines.Author: Mia Lamar
Headlines.Headline: Praxair Increasing Prices On Nitrogen, Other Gases Starting June 1

PARAGRAPH.#text: DOW JONES NEWSWIRES Industrial gas company Praxair Inc. PX will enact price increases on a number of its offerings next month, a move it said is necessary to support ongoing investment in its business and offset increasing production costs. Praxair, the largest industrial gas company in the Americas, also noted unspecified supply and demand imbalances for some of its products in the U.S. and Canada as cause for the increased prices. The effort, effective June 1, will see prices for nitrogen and oxygen rise by up to 12%, while argon and hydrogen prices will increase by up to 18%.

Headlines.SeoHeadline: Morning MarketBeat: Bernanke Takes The Stage
Headlines.Author: Dave Kansas
Headlines.Headline: Morning MarketBeat: Bernanke Takes The Stage

PARAGRAPH.#text: Pre-Market Brief:Market Tone: Cautious ahead of Bernanke press conference. Dollar mixed, Treasurys lower, oil slightly higher, gold little changedOvernight Action: BP Net Profit Rises; S&P Changes Japan Outlook to Negative;Watch for: Fed rate decision and press conference,  earnings from Ebay, Starbucks, Boeing, ConocoPhillipsThe Breakfast BriefingToday, all eyes will go to the Bearded One.Federal Reserve Chairman Ben Bernanke will face the scribes in a first-ever press conference at 2:15 p.m. EDT. The Fed says the press conference is aimed at increasing transparency. It?s more likely to be a tour de force in sleep-inducing obfuscation.The Federal Open Market Committee, the Fed?s policy group, will issue its statement at 1230 p.m. EDT, ahead of Big Ben?s 2:15 p.m. EDT date with the press. It is difficult to imagine that Big Ben will break new ground at the microphone, but there?s always hope. Jean-Claude Trichet, head of the European Central Bank, used a press briefing to signal that the ECB planned to raise rates this month, which it did early this month. (The ECB, like other central banks, has held press briefings for years.)The dollar?s recent weakness ? the dollar index is at a three-year low and the euro is at a fresh 52-week high ? underscores the belief that the Fed is in no rush to tighten its extraordinarily loose monetary policy. Our friends at Real Time Economics offer a nifty primer on how to interpret the words and phrases of Big Ben. (The over/under betting line for number of chuckles Big Ben gets: three.)The Fed, in its statement, is expected to say it will finish its $600 billion quantitative easing program (QE2) on schedule in June. It is also not expected to raise too many alarms about looming interest-rate moves. The Fed-funds futures sees only a 26% chance that the Fed will raise rates to 0.5% by next February.As investors fidget about what the Bearded One might say, earnings will come in full force once again. On Tuesday, strong earnings from 3M, Ford Motor, Delta Air Lines and UPS helped set a robust tone from the opening bell.The Dow Jones Industrial Average gained 115.49 to 12595.37, its highest close since June 5, 2008. The Nasdaq Composite jumped 21.66 to 2847.54, its highest close since Oct. 31, 2007. And the S&P 500 gained 11.99 to 1347.24, its best close since June 17, 2008.On Wednesday, earnings will come from all directions, with energy and aerospace dominating.On the energy front, Baker Hughes, Cabot Oil & Gas, BP, ConocoPhillips, ENI, Hess Corp. and National Oil Well Varco report. Energy companies have reported strong earnings, boosted by rising oil prices. Boeing, General Dynamics and Northrop Grumman report on the aerospace side. Lockheed Martin reported solid earnings Tuesday; its shares rose more than 2%.Other notable earnings: Norfolk Southern, Whirlpool, Las Vegas Sands, Akamai, Baidu, Dr. Pepper Snapple, Green Mountain Coffee Roasters, eBay, Credit Suisse, Southern Co., and Barrick Gold. (A fuller list of key earnings due today are down below.)On the economic front, March durable goods orders are expected to show a 2.4% gain, reversing an unexpected decline in February. Also, the Energy Department reports petroleum data mid-morning. Crude oil stocks are expected to rise 1.1 million barrels and gasoline stocks are expected to decline once again. (A complete list of G7 economic reports due on Wednesday is at the end of this post.)The market surge on Tuesday had some chin-scratchers arguing that investors were buying the rumor (Bernanke will be really soft/nice/kind/luvy-duvy) in anticipation of selling that news (the actual statement/press briefing). That?s an old, arthritic Wall Street saw. But sometimes even the hoary sayings get it right.L?Etoile du Nord-Dave KansasMARKET SNAPIndex                            Level         Chg            Pct. #text: Dealers were positioning for a down day Tuesday after European and Asian stocks weakened overnight as President Bush held to a hawkish tone on Iraq.     Eventually, the routers could help AOL offer so-called quality of service features for
    which customers would pay extra to guarantee immediate delivery of high-priority
    communications, Cisco said. Such features are required for voice or video traffic to be
    delivered without interruption over the Internet. Cisco shares gained 2 3/4 to 100 7/8,
    while AOL rose 6 3/4 to 111 3/16.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: AOL looks to Cisco for help 8-18-98
